- High Voltage has features that partially overlap with my tastes—layered harmonized guitars and anthemic choruses correspond to my liking for multi‑tracked guitars and sing‑along choruses, and the tight mixes that keep vocals and guitars forward are positive. However, its emphasis on “raw live‑band energy,” “aggressive warm‑analog drums/bass,” and “vintage‑style mastering” indicates a less glossy, less studio‑polished aesthetic than I emphasized as my current priority. I explicitly disliked distant/muddy live mixes and lo‑fi or production choices that favor raw energy at the expense of clarity and instrumental nuance. While High Voltage may be enjoyable for fans of concise riffy rock, its rawer, live‑oriented character is a poorer match for my current preference for pristine, radio‑ready polish and the kind of detailed, intimate mastering described for Reflections.
Why I chose Reflections and rejected High Voltage (specifics tied to preferences/dislikes):
- Vocal focus and storytelling: Reflections is explicitly singer‑centered with warm midrange vocals and emotionally direct storytelling—this satisfies my preference for vocal‑forward mixes and melodic variety. High Voltage is more riff‑forward and blends vocals into the band sound; that blending can reduce the kind of vocal clarity and multi‑layered harmony focus I favor.
- Production polish and detail: Reflections’ dynamic mastering that preserves sparkle and intimacy maps directly onto my desire for polished mixes that reveal subtle detail. High Voltage’s vintage, raw energy and aggressive analog rhythm section suggest a tougher, less glossy presentation that risks sidelining some of the instrumental nuance I prize.
