- Sequencing and full‑disc reward: Both releases reference sequencing that rewards listening, but Reflections is explicitly described as thoughtful for front‑to‑back replay. Given my preference for coherent pacing, the greatest hits collection—so long as it’s well mastered and not sonically thin—meets that need. The description of Reflections makes clear it is not the kind of thin, harsh compilation I dislike.
- Avoiding disliked production traits: My dislikes (lo‑fi mastering, muddy live mixes, flattened melodic storytelling) are more likely to be triggered by High Voltage’s “raw live‑band energy” and aggressive vintage mastering than by Reflections’ described dynamic, intimate mastering and restrained orchestration.
In short, while High Voltage contains some elements I like (harmonized guitars and anthemic choruses), Reflections better matches the core of what I now especially enjoy—vocal‑forward, meticulously produced recordings with tasteful orchestration and polished mastering that retain instrumental detail—so I select Reflections: Carly Simon's Greatest Hits.

