Overall, the combination of era‑faithful tape sheen, tactile midrange, lyrical vocal placement with natural imaging, and restrained mastering makes Greatest Hits, Vol. 1 a closer fit to the warm, song‑first late‑70s AOR presentation I favor.
Why I reject the In‑the‑room analog mixes:
- Too immediate/punchy for my ideal late‑70s sheen: while the in‑the‑room mixes share many positive traits (subtle tape warmth, minimal compression, punchy drums, tactile bass, revealing micro‑detail, and lush harmonies), their emphasis on “punchy drums,” “midrange grit,” and “immediate yet spacious lead vocals” leans toward a more upfront, hard‑edged in‑the‑room presentation. My preference leans toward slightly softened drum attack, gentle compression and a warmer, more diffuse vocal reverb that places vocals in a rounded analog midrange. The in‑the‑room emphasis on uncompressed micro‑detail and midrange grit risks producing the kind of overly immediate or vocally forward sound that can approach the thin/close‑miked or sterile intimacy I dislike. 
