The user updates his self-description as follows: I enjoy big, widescreen 1970s AOR–style mixes: layered overdriven electrics and roomy natural reverb that give instruments and vocals believable space while retaining breath and consonant detail; upfront, tactile midrange vocals that are present without sounding unnaturally close; tasteful multi‑tracked harmonies, analog tape warmth, restrained remasters that preserve headroom and transient snap; punchy, propulsive low end and tight rhythmic pockets that drive momentum beneath the sheen. I still favor in‑the‑room analog mixes that preserve dynamics and micro‑detail, subtle tape sheen, lyric‑forward clarity with clear midrange grit, articulate drums and tactile bass, and mastering that leaves headroom. Dislikes: thin or gravelly close‑miked vocals forced unrealistically forward; mixes that are relentlessly dry and single‑plane (no natural ambience); loudness‑crushed or over‑polished mastering; dense muddy low‑mids that bury detail; and sterile, overly softened transient attack.

The positive CD has the following updated information: Authentic 1976 AOR mix: big layered overdriven guitars and roomy natural reverb, yet preserved transient snap and restrained remastering. Upfront tactile midrange vocals with breath detail, punchy propulsive low end, tight rhythmic pockets, tasteful multi‑part harmonies and analog tape warmth—wide but dynamically alive.

